    "slug": "conflict-in-the-horn-of-africa-acled",
    "summary": "Political violence in the Horn of Africa escalates as TPLF's move to fully control Tigray threatens peace and Jihadist groups expand their reach across the region.",
    "content": "The Horn of Africa is currently experiencing high levels of political violence and instability, owing to a number of civil conflicts, violence by militias and militant Islamist groups, and insurgencies. The region typically includes Ethiopia, Somalia, Djibouti, and Eritrea, with a broader definition encompassing Kenya, Sudan, and South Sudan.\n\nRecent reports highlight that Ethiopia's elections were never going to change the government, but instead acted as a stress multiplier, worsening existing conflicts. Meanwhile, the TPLF's reinstatement of the 2020 regional government in Tigray threatens the fragile peace in the region and risks triggering another full-blown battle.\n\nJihadist groups pose a growing and expanding threat across Africa, with the ADF ramping up violence in Ituri amid the Ebola outbreak, and JNIM launching a deadly campaign against Dozo militias in Mali. Islamist militants are exerting growing military strength in targeting state forces and civilians across several regions of the continent.\n\nThese developments underscore the complex security challenges facing the Horn of Africa, as multiple actors vie for control and power, often at the expense of civilian lives and regional stability.",
