    "slug": "great-power-competition-in-the-horn-of-africa-youtube",
    "summary": "A Hudson Institute panel discusses the strategic importance of the Horn of Africa and the roles of the US, China, and Russia in the region.",
    "content": "The Horn of Africa is one of the world's most sensitive and strategic regions, overlooking vital shipping lanes connecting Asia and Europe, sharing a maritime border with the Middle East, and boasting thousands of miles of Indian Ocean coastline. It is home to Africa's second most populous country, Ethiopia, and key ports like Djibouti, which hosts Chinese, American, and other military bases. However, deep political tensions and a history of conflict make effective diplomacy challenging.\n\nIn a recent webinar hosted by the Hudson Institute in collaboration with the Israel-Africa Institute, experts discussed the actions of global powers—the United States, China, and Russia—in the Horn. They analyzed strategies, motivations, and potential impacts on the region. Panelists Joshua Mazervi, Mosh Turdan, and Ebeneza Oadare explored why the Horn matters geopolitically and how external actors shape its future.\n\nThe discussion highlighted the region's strategic significance, with Oadare underscoring three key points: its location near critical sea lanes, its role as a hub for international military presence, and the complications arising from local conflicts. The panel also addressed how competition among great powers influences governance, security, and development in the Horn, raising questions about sovereignty and regional stability.",
