    "title": "Horn of Africa | Chatham House – International Affairs Think Tank",
    "slug": "horn-of-africa-chatham-house-international-affairs-think-tank",
    "summary": "Chatham House research analyzes the Horn of Africa's evolving politics, conflict dynamics, and governance challenges, with a focus on supporting stable transitions and regional integration.",
    "content": "Chatham House's Horn of Africa research program examines the region's complex political transitions, conflict dynamics, and governance challenges. The region includes countries such as Somalia, Ethiopia, Sudan, South Sudan, Djibouti, Eritrea, and Kenya, each facing distinct yet interconnected issues.\n\nPolitical transitions across the Horn are marked by turbulence as civilians seek more representative and decentralized governance structures. In Somalia, ongoing constitutional amendments by President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud have created a political impasse, while Ethiopia navigates persistent instability and simmering regional tensions ahead of elections on 1 June. These domestic struggles are compounded by transnational conflicts that connect local flashpoints to wider cross-border dynamics through supply chains and militant networks.\n\nClimate change and recurrent drought exacerbate these challenges, driving food insecurity, displacement, and hardship. The impacts are most severe for vulnerable populations, who often bear the brunt of both environmental stress and armed conflict. Despite strong local cross-border ties in many areas, mutual suspicion and competition between states limit the capacity for collective responses to regional development and governance problems.\n\nThe research aims to support more stable political and governance transitions, greater regional integration, and effective policy interventions. By analyzing how local conflicts connect to broader regional trends, Chatham House seeks to inform approaches that address root causes and promote long-term stability in the Horn of Africa.",
