    "id": "news-1783338975093-18",
    "title": "Reshaping the Horn of Africa: Dams, Ports, and Peace Deals | GJIA",
    "slug": "reshaping-the-horn-of-africa-dams-ports-and-peace-deals-gjia",
    "summary": "In the Horn of Africa, unconventional deals involving Ethiopia, Somaliland, and external actors are reshaping regional dynamics, with a focus on port access, statehood recognition, and peace support operations.",
    "content": "The Horn of Africa is witnessing a profound reorientation of interstate and intrastate security dynamics, driven by a series of unconventional transactions and alliances. A key flashpoint emerged in January 2024 when Somaliland signed a Memorandum of Understanding with Ethiopia, granting Addis Ababa access to 19 kilometers of coastline near the Port of Berbera in exchange for potential political recognition. This move has been met with fierce opposition from the Federal Republic of Somalia, which views it as a violation of its sovereignty. The ensuing tensions have prompted Turkish-mediated formal talks between Ethiopia and Somalia since December 2024, yet the underlying issues remain unresolved, including the status of Somaliland, fair sea access for landlocked states, and the broader geopolitical chess game in the region.\n\nBeyond the Somaliland-Ethiopia deal, the region is grappling with multiple interconnected challenges. The Nile River dispute continues to strain relations between upstream and downstream states, while peace support operations are increasingly instrumentalized by both regional and extra-regional actors. Proxy conflicts are destabilizing fragile alliances and peace agreements, with countries like Ethiopia, Sudan, Somalia, and South Sudan embroiled in internal and cross-border strife. The involvement of external powers, while sometimes aimed at mediation, often exacerbates tensions by playing into existing rivalries and ambitions.\n\nTo address these complexities, the authors argue that regional and continental inter-governmental organizations must convene urgent consultations. Such dialogues should navigate the intricate geopolitical landscape, consider the security implications of ongoing peace operations, and work toward durable peace. Crucially, states in the Horn of Africa must reaffirm their commitment to regional integration by resisting the temptation of proxy engagements from both regional and extra-regional actors. The path to stability lies in collaborative rather than competitive approaches, ensuring that the region's resources—from ports to dams—become tools for cooperation rather than conflict.",
    "source": "gjia.georgetown.edu",
    "original_url": "https://gjia.georgetown.edu/global-governance/unconventional-transactions-and-alliances-in-the-horn-of-africa-statehood-dams-ports-and-peace-support-operations/",
