    "summary": "Somalia and Saudi Arabia signed a military cooperation pact, shifting Red Sea security dynamics amid regional rivalries and new geopolitical tensions following Israel's recognition of Somaliland.",
    "content": "The Horn of Africa is rapidly emerging as a critical geopolitical flashpoint, with Somalia and Saudi Arabia signing a landmark military cooperation agreement on 9 February in Riyadh. The pact, announced on the sidelines of the World Defence Show, is expected to focus on military training, technical assistance, and defence capacity-building for Somalia's armed forces, though specific provisions remain undisclosed.\n\nThis development comes amid intensifying regional rivalries following Israel's recognition of Somaliland and growing competition among Gulf powers, including Qatar and the UAE. The Red Sea Corridor, handling nearly 15% of global trade and 30% of container traffic, has become a strategic prize. Saudi Arabia's expanding role as a security guarantor carries far-reaching implications for maritime stability, regional sovereignty disputes, and the broader balance of power across West Asia and East Africa.\n\nAs Ethiopia seeks sea access and Egypt safeguards its Suez Canal interests, the Saudi-Somalia defence pact underscores a rapidly evolving strategic contest in one of the world's most vital maritime theatres. The agreement also comes against a backdrop of heightened tensions over Somaliland's status, the Ethiopia-Somaliland MoU on Berbera Port, and ongoing Houthi attacks on Red Sea shipping, further complicating the security landscape.",
